{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627096"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:44:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:44:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17099"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17099"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.04,0,0.8,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9789"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76515"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9789"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17099"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62012"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5109"},{"type":"tags","id":"7005"},{"type":"tags","id":"10087"},{"type":"tags","id":"10130"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22967"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23111"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76515"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIodine is an essential micronutrient that is important for healthy thyroid function. The thyroid gland actively concentrates iodide from the bloodstream through the sodium-iodide symporter.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the role of iodine in thyroid hormone synthesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Facilitates uptake of selenium into thyroid cells","Stimulates release of thyroid-stimulating hormone","Increases thyroid peroxidase production","Combines with tyrosine residues to form thyroid hormones","Functions as a cofactor for thyroid peroxidase enzyme"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that iodine \u003Cstrong\u003Ecombines with tyrosine residues to form thyroid hormones\u003C/strong\u003E. After being actively transported into thyroid follicular cells as iodide, it is oxidised by thyroid peroxidase and incorporated into tyrosine residues on thyroglobulin. This forms monoiodotyrosine (MIT) and diiodotyrosine (DIT), which then couple to form triiodothyronine (T3) and thyroxine (T4).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitates uptake of selenium into thyroid cells\u003C/strong\u003E - While selenium is important for deiodinase enzymes, iodine does not influence selenium transport\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates release of thyroid-stimulating hormone\u003C/strong\u003E - TSH release is regulated by hypothalamic TRH and negative feedback from thyroid hormones\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases thyroid peroxidase production\u003C/strong\u003E - not the role of iodine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFunctions as a cofactor for thyroid peroxidase enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E - Iodine is a substrate for thyroid peroxidase, which uses hydrogen peroxide as a cofactor \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorporation of iodine into thyroglobulin is essential for thyroid hormone synthesis. Iodine deficiency can lead to inadequate thyroid hormone production and goitre.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Iodine is essential for thyroid hormone synthesis as it is incorporated with tyrosine residues within thyroglobulins to form T3 and T4.","Thyroid peroxidase enzyme oxidises iodide to iodine radicals  and then incorporates them onto tyrosine residues as part of thyroid hormone synthesis","Iodination of tyrosine residues produces monoiodotyrosine (MIT) and diiodotyrosine (DIT), which combine to form T3 and T4."],"references":["Brent GA. Mechanisms of thyroid hormone action. J Clin Invest. 2012 Sep;122(9):3035-43. doi: 10.1172/JCI60047. Epub 2012 Sep 4. PMID: 22945636; PMCID: PMC3433956.","Sorrenti S, Baldini E, Pironi D, et al. Iodine: Its Role in Thyroid Hormone Biosynthesis and Beyond. Nutrients. 2021;13(12):4469. Published 2021 Dec 14. doi:10.3390/nu13124469"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62012"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17099"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62012"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T16:07:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T16:08:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9789"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76515"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCou